    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. So, when we're talking about the 'judicial activism' side of things, is it fair to say that those critics are essentially arguing that substantive due process is just a way for judges to bypass the democratic process and impose their own personal values on the country?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, that is precisely the core of the criticism from those who oppose broad interpretations of substantive due process. Critics argue that when judges invent unenumerated rights, they are substituting their personal, often progressive, moral philosophies for the will of the people expressed through elected legislatures. This view holds that the Constitution should only guarantee rights explicitly enumerated within its text, reserving policy decisions to the democratic branches of government. This perspective champions the idea that the judiciary should defer to the legislative branch unless a clear constitutional violation is present.",
      "source": "target",
